      <div xml:id="NA189-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai melinta talaimakaḷait tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforts HER who has become weak in the time of separation.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA189">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            tammala tillā nannayan taruḷi</l>
<l>            yiṉṉum vārā rāyiṉuñ ceṉṉiyar</l>
<l>            teṟalaruṅ kaṭavuṇ muṉṉar cīṟiyāḻ</l>
<l>            narampicait taṉṉa viṉkuraṟ kurukiṉ</l>
<l>            kaṅkai vaṅkam pōkuvar kollō </l>
<l>            vevviṉai ceyvarko ṟāmē vevviṉaik</l>
<l>            kolaival vēṭṭuvaṉ valaiparintu pōkiya</l>
<l>            kāṉap puṟaviṉ cēval vāynūṟ</l>
<l>            cilampi yañciṉai verūu</l>
<l>            malaṅka lulavaiyaṅ kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">        Even if he doesn't come right now,</l>
<l rend="indent">        being considerate [and] longing for us who don't exist without him,</l>
<l>    will he go by ship on the Gangā,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        with herons(?)<note place="foot">What is a sweet-voiced <term xml:lang="ta">kuruku</term>? Either we have to conclude that the word means also other birds besides waders (T.V.G. wants it to be a nightingale or a cuckoo), or the point is that in the fabulous Gangetic area even herons have beautiful voices.</note>, [their] voices sweet as if the strings were</l>
<l rend="indent2">         sounded on the small lute, in front of the god rare in wrath,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            by excellent [bards]?</l>
<l>    What work will he do, he,</l>
<l>    who has gone to traverse the wilderness of swaying branches<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ulavai</term> is a homonym for either dry/green branch or wind, and the first <term xml:lang="ta">cīr</term> can either be read alaṅkal ("swaying") or malaṅkal ("being agitated" = "whirling"). T.V.G. reads the wind version: "... the wilderness of whirling winds".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">        where the cock of the forest dove, gone after it had broken free</l>
<l rend="indent">        from the net of the hunter strong in killing, [his] cruel task,</l>
<l>        [now] is frightened on the pretty branch [even] by the spider</l>
<l rend="indent3">        that [makes] threads from [its] mouth?</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
